Investigators discover dangerous building defect in A380-Triebwerken 
The A380 has obviously a large safety problem. 
Investigators discovered a possible building defect, which can lead to a "catastrophic engine loss" with the investigation of a made an emergency landing machine. 
The airline Qantas wants to sue now the engine manufacturer. 
The passengers of the made an emergency landing Qantas airbus at the beginning of November had obviously many more luck than so far well-known: The Australian air security authority determined and warns a large safety problem with its investigations with the engines of some A380-Maschinen - now of a possible building defect. 
The potential defect would have heavy consequences: During an oil hose connector it could produce fatigue cracks and leakages, was called it in one on this Thursday published statement of the authority ATSB. 
This could have led to "a catastrophic engine loss." 
Manufactured engines are affected in 20 airplanes of the A380-Reihe by Rolls-Royces. 
Among them is the Qantas airbus, which had to make an emergency landing on 4 November in Singapore. 
The Australian airline introduced now legal steps against the British turbine manufacturer. 
It submitted a complaint reason with an Australian Federal court in Sydney, which make further legal measures for it possible against the enterprise. 
Qantas boss of Alan Joyce said, its airline compensation for the incident at the beginning of November will require. 
With the fire of the engine parts had separated and the bearing areas had damaged. 
Rolls-Royce constituted an oil fire as a cause for the damage. 
After the incident now world-wide engines must be replaced up to 40. 
The Australian investigators announced to accomplish further safety tests at the superjumbo jets which are equipped with the engines concerned. 
The safety recommendation is the result of a co-operation with Rolls-Royces, said ATSB spokesman Martin Dolan. 
The safety problem was considered sufficiently important, in order to inform all concerning. 
After the forced landing of the Qantas machine the airline had kept its A380-Flotte lasting for weeks at the ground. 
Singapore Airlines let about three of its eleven A380 temporary at the ground. 
The engine replaced Lufthansa with a A380 as precautionary measure. 
The two-story fliers is the largest passenger airline of the world. 
